terman  , and for the type compare   Maidens  ,   Monks  ,   Parsons  .","variant of   Master  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","English:"],"variants":[{"name":"Master","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Amar, Dhimant, Pravin, Amit, Aruna, Bhanu, Gaurang, Gopal, Haren, Jagu, Jayesh, Kalpesh.","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>maister</i> ‘master’ (Old French <i>maistre</i>). The word had a wide range of applications, and the reference in surnames may be to a schoolmaster, to the master of a farm or house, to the master of an apprentice, or to a ship's captain. In Scotland the eldest sons of barons and the uncles of lords were called <i>Masters</i>, but this is not primarily a Scottish surname.","German: dialect form of   Meister   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]},{"name":"Maidens","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire):","occupational or habitational name from Middle English <i>(atte) maydenes</i> ‘(at the) maiden's or maidens' (house)’, a name for someone who lived or worked at such a house. Compare   Masters   and   Parsons  .","post-medieval variant of   Maiden  , with excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Marsters","meanings":["English: variant of   Masters  . <i>Marsters</i> is the predominant surname on Palmerston Island, Cook Islands, South Pacific, deriving from a settler and owner reputedly born in Leicestershire."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":46,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonie